Ask HN: Has anyone tried themes with AI/ML generation?
text:
Thematic/decorative uses of AI/ML art seem like they'd be less of a copyright-issue, and maybe as a result, a bit more free-form fun.

Like imagine if instead of a hex code in your HN profile, you could type in a prompt:

"A dungeon theme with light text on a dark slate background. The Y logo should look like lava within a glowing stone. I want some swords placed along the sides for decoration."

"Apple-inspired typography and rainbow-colored hyperlinks, with a few cat faces scattered around."

"A dot matrix printer page with some random ballpoint pen doodles of fractals along the margins."

Could this work? Would it make skeuomorphic design even more popular again, because it wouldn't be as reliant on artists anymore?

Ask HN: Why do games (as media) make so much money?
text:
We often hear how the games industry is bigger in terms of $ than film & music put together. But looking around it's still less universal than e.g. TV (±"everyone" watches TV but not everyone plays video games).

How come games make more money as an industry than other media?
